## AppThemeBinding — Automatic Light/Dark Mode

The simplest approach is `AppThemeBinding`, which picks a value based on the OS theme automatically:

### XAML

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             BackgroundColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=White, Dark=#1E1E1E}">

    <VerticalStackLayout Padding="20" Spacing="15">

        <Label Text="Welcome"
               FontSize="24"
               TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=#333333, Dark=#FFFFFF}" />

        <Label Text="This page follows the system theme."
               TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=#666666, Dark=#CCCCCC}" />

        <Button Text="Get Started"
                TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=White, Dark=White}"
                BackgroundColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=#2196F3, Dark=#BB86FC}" />

    </VerticalStackLayout>
</ContentPage>
```

Every `AppThemeBinding` takes a `Light` and `Dark` value — the framework switches automatically when the device theme changes.

### C# equivalent

Use `SetAppThemeColor` (for colors) or `SetAppTheme<T>` (for any property):

```csharp
var page = new ContentPage();
page.SetAppThemeColor(ContentPage.BackgroundColorProperty, Colors.White, Color.FromArgb("#1E1E1E"));

var title = new Label { Text = "Welcome", FontSize = 24 };
title.SetAppThemeColor(Label.TextColorProperty, Color.FromArgb("#333333"), Colors.White);

var button = new Button { Text = "Get Started" };
button.SetAppThemeColor(Button.BackgroundColorProperty, Color.FromArgb("#2196F3"), Color.FromArgb("#BB86FC"));
```

### Detecting & overriding the theme in code

```csharp
// Read current theme
AppTheme current = Application.Current!.RequestedTheme;

// Force dark mode regardless of OS
Application.Current!.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Dark;

// Follow the system again
Application.Current!.UserAppTheme = AppTheme.Unspecified;

// React to changes
Application.Current!.RequestedThemeChanged += (s, e) =>
{
    // e.RequestedTheme is the new theme
};
```

### Android requirement

Ensure `MainActivity` includes `ConfigChanges.UiMode` or theme changes will restart the activity instead of firing events:

```csharp
[Activity(ConfigurationChanges = ConfigChanges.ScreenSize
                               | ConfigChanges.Orientation
                               | ConfigChanges.UiMode   // ← required
                               | ...)]
public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity { }
```

### When to upgrade to ResourceDictionary swapping

`AppThemeBinding` covers light vs. dark. If you later need **custom branded themes** or **more than two themes**, move colors into separate `ResourceDictionary` files, bind with `DynamicResource`, and swap dictionaries at runtime. Let me know if you'd like an example of that approach.
